Orson Tsang (@orsythehorsy) shares his experience working with Strength & Conditioning Coach and Manual Therapist James Lu at Lu Strength & Therapy!
___________________
.
" I've been training the sport of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu for 8 years and working in physically demanding industries my whole life. One and a half years into BJJ, I started to lose sensation and feeling in my arms. It took me dozens of different doctors/ therapists, trainers and many years to find something that worked this effectively.

James has guided me towards recovery and educating me on how to fix and prevent future injuries. He has also helped me improve my strength and conditioning which allows me to push harder in training and to recover faster. It was also important for me to find a therapist that understands the sport and needs of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu!

It's truly his goal to "not to see you". "
.
🎥: @neoncowvideo @neoncowvideo @neoncowvideo
.

🚨 𝟑 𝐄𝐀𝐒𝐘 𝐋𝐎𝐖𝐄𝐑 𝐁𝐀𝐂𝐊 𝐒𝐓𝐑𝐄𝐓𝐂𝐇𝐄𝐒! 🚨

Do you complain about your lower back constantly being stiff?

Mobilizing the lower back and hips and promoting healthy movement in these areas can help loosen up the joints. These exercises should also be accompanied by some sort of strengthening exercises (in our next post) to help cement the results.

1️⃣ 𝗙𝗢𝗔𝗠 𝗥𝗢𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗥 𝗧𝗪𝗜𝗦𝗧:
Lay face up with the legs bent to roughly 90 degrees with a foam roller in between the knees. Stretch both arms to the side with the palms on the ground. Slowly lower the legs to one side of the body and repeat on the opposite side.

2️⃣ 𝗦𝗘𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗪𝗜𝗡𝗗𝗠𝗜𝗟𝗟𝗦:
Sit on a chair or bench with the feet wider than shoulder width apart. Grab a hold of the opposite foot with the hand. Reach the free arm up towards the ceiling while following the finger tips with your eyes.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞 𝗘𝗫𝗧𝗘𝗡𝗦𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. Place both hands on the lower back and hip area. Thrust the hips forward while using your hands to add extra pressure. Pull the hips backwards to the starting position and repeat.
.
🚨 𝗦𝗔𝗩𝗘 𝟮𝟱% 𝗢𝗙𝗙 𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗕𝗨𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗧𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗢𝗙 𝗬𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗟𝗢𝗪𝗘𝗥 𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞 𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗚𝗥𝗔𝗠! 🚨 𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗞 𝗜𝗡 𝗜𝗡 𝗕𝗜𝗢! 🚨
.

🚨 𝐅𝐈𝐗 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐂𝐋𝐈𝐂𝐊𝐈𝐍𝐆 𝐒𝐇𝐎𝐔𝐋𝐃𝐄𝐑𝐒! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃ 
.
Do you complain about your shoulders snapping, clicking and/or cracking?

Oftentimes, different soft tissues such as tendons and muscles can "snap" off bony protuberances when moving the shoulder around. While there may not be any pain present, continuous snapping/clicking can cause wear and tear on the joint and tissues over time. Strengthening the tissues is crucial when it comes to correcting this dysfunction.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗜𝗗𝗘 𝗟𝗬𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗥𝗢𝗧𝗔𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Lay on your side and with your head rested on your arm. Grab a hold of a dumbbell with the opposite hand with the elbow pinched towards the torso. Rotate the arms outwards so that the palm is facing downwards and hold this position.

2️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗣𝗨𝗡𝗖𝗛𝗘𝗦:
Attach a resistance band around a stationary object such as a squat rack at elbow height. Grab a hold of the resistance band with the far side hand and walk outwards. Have the palm facing towards the squat rack and press the band forward and backwards.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗕𝗜𝗟𝗜𝗧𝗬 𝗕𝗔𝗟𝗟 𝗨𝗣𝗣𝗘𝗥𝗖𝗨𝗧𝗦:
Sandwich a stability ball between a wall and the outside of your wrist. Drive the arm into the ball while performing an exaggerated upper cut up towards the ceiling with the arm. Lower the arm back down and repeat.
.
🚨 𝗪𝗔𝗡𝗧 𝗧𝗢 𝗕𝗨𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗧𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗢𝗙 𝗬𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗦𝗛𝗢𝗨𝗟𝗗𝗘𝗥𝗦? 🚨
🚀 𝗦𝗔𝗩𝗘 𝟮𝟱% 𝗢𝗙𝗙 𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗕𝗨𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗧𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗢𝗙 𝗬𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗦𝗛𝗢𝗨𝗟𝗗𝗘𝗥𝗦 𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗚𝗥𝗔𝗠! 
⬆️ 𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗞 𝗜𝗡 𝗧𝗛𝗘 𝗕𝗜𝗢! ⬆️

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐓𝐈𝐆𝐇𝐓 𝐂𝐀𝐋𝐕𝐄𝐒! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The calf muscle consists of two different heads, the gastrocnemius (more superficial head) and the soleus (the deeper head).

Excessive tension in the calves can be caused from repetitive strain disorders, muscular imbalances and possibly even injury. This can lead to possible dysfunctions such as contributing to a lack of ankle mobility, hamstring stiffness and even lower back tension.

1️⃣ 𝗔𝗡𝗞𝗟𝗘 𝗠𝗢𝗕𝗜𝗟𝗜𝗭𝗔𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡:
Grab onto a squat rack or door frame and squat down as low as possible with the feet flat on the ground. Lift the chest up towards the ceiling and slowly rock your weight side to side until a stretch is felt in your ankles.

2️⃣ 𝗞𝗘𝗧𝗧𝗟𝗘𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗖𝗔𝗟𝗙 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Sit on the ground and place the musculature of the lower leg on top of the handle of a kettlebell. Place the opposite foot on top of the leg and slowly flex and extend the ankle while focusing on more tender areas of the calf muscle.

3️⃣ 𝗛𝗘𝗘𝗟 𝗗𝗥𝗢𝗣 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Stand on an elevated platform such as a plyometric box and holding onto a squat rack. Hang the heels of the feet off the ledge while leaning the torso forward towards the squat rack until a stretch is felt.
.

🚨 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐇𝐎𝐔𝐋𝐃𝐄𝐑 𝐌𝐎𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃ 
.
The latissimus dorsi is a broad, flat muscle that connects the upper extremity to the lower portion of the torso and plays a major role in stability.

Excessive tension in this muscle can cause dysfunctions such as same sided shoulder and lower back pain along with difficulty with overhead movements such as shoulder presses and/or snatches. A combination of strengthening, releasing and mobilizing can all help restore balance to the area.

1️⃣ 𝗕𝗘𝗡𝗖𝗛 𝗟𝗔𝗧 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Start kneeling in front of a bench and holding onto a dowel. Place the elbows on top of the bench. Sink your hips back towards your heels while pulling the dowel back and behind the neck until a stretch is felt.

2️⃣ 𝗞𝗘𝗧𝗧𝗟𝗘𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗟𝗔𝗧 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Lay on your side and position the musculature of the outside of the back (where the arm meets the back) on the handle of a kettlebell. Reach the up overhead with the palms facing the ceiling. Slowly sink your weight into the kettlebell until a release.

3️⃣ 𝗗𝗨𝗠𝗕𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗪𝗜𝗡𝗗𝗠𝗜𝗟𝗟𝗦:
Start in a half kneeling position and hold onto a dumbbell on the same side as the forward leg. Lift the dumbbell overhead. Lower the opposite hand to the ground while continuously driving the dumbbell up towards the ceiling.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐐𝐔𝐀𝐓 𝐌𝐎𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.

Having a lack of mobility in the ankles, hips and thoracic spine during a squat can cause the body to compensate with other areas of the body.

Issues such as knee pain, hip impingement and lower back discomfort (and even elbow pain!) can all be a result of not having an adequate amount of mobility in the right areas. Improving and/or restoring one's mobility should be top priority when it comes to building a stronger and pain free squat.

1️⃣ 𝗙𝗨𝗟𝗟 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗪𝗔𝗟𝗟 𝗦𝗟𝗜𝗗𝗘𝗦:
Squat down in front of a wall with your head, middle back and lower back against the wall/squat rack. Tuck the chin back and have the arms to the side similar to a shoulder press position. Press the arms overhead and back down to the starting position.

2️⃣ 𝗙𝗨𝗟𝗟 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗣𝗥𝗘𝗦𝗦 𝗢𝗨𝗧:
Start in your preferred squat stance (preferably feet slightly wider than shoulder width apart) with a bumper plate held a few inches away from the chest. Squat down as low as you can and press the bumper plate forward, followed by sitting down into a deeper squat.

3️⃣ 𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗗𝗥𝗨𝗣𝗘𝗗 𝗥𝗢𝗖𝗞𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞𝗦:
Start on all fours with the hands underneath the shoulders and knees under the hips. Place a foam roller on the lower back. Slowly pull the hips back towards the feet while maintaining a neutral spine and avoid having the foam roller fall from the lower back.

🚨 𝐂𝐎𝐑𝐑𝐄𝐂𝐓 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐇𝐔𝐍𝐂𝐇 𝐁𝐀𝐂𝐊! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃ 
.
Hyperkyphosis (also commonly known as a hunchback) is a dysfunction in which the upper spine has an excessive curvature.

Some possible factors contributing to hyperkyphosis are poor posture, muscular imbalances and simply not being aware of your overall posture. Promoting more mobility in the thoracic spine along with strengthening the tissues responsible for keeping the spine upright should be top priority.

1️⃣ 𝗕𝗘𝗡𝗖𝗛 𝗧𝗛𝗢𝗥𝗔𝗖𝗜𝗖 𝗘𝗫𝗧𝗘𝗡𝗦𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Start in a kneeling position with the fingers interlocked behind the neck and elbows rested on a bench. Sink your hips backwards while dropping the chest towards the ground. Imagine pulling the chest as low as possible towards the floor.

2️⃣ 𝗠𝗜𝗡𝗜 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗 𝗦𝗛𝗢𝗩𝗘𝗟𝗦:
Sit on a bench with a mini band around the wrist. Bend the arms to roughly 90 degrees with the fist facing forward. Punch the fist up and away from you while maintaining a 90 degree bend in the arms at all times. Lower the arms back down and repeat.

3️⃣ 𝗟𝗢𝗡𝗚 𝗦𝗜𝗧𝗧𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗪 𝗣𝗥𝗘𝗦𝗦:
Sit on the ground with the legs fully extended in front of you. Place a strength band around the feet and held in front of your shoulders. While maintaining an upright torso, press the band overhead and slowly lower back to starting position.
.
🚨 𝗡𝗘𝗘𝗗 𝗠𝗬 𝗛𝗘𝗟𝗣 𝗔𝗡𝗗 𝗪𝗔𝗡𝗧 𝗧𝗢 𝗠𝗢𝗩𝗘 𝗣𝗔𝗜𝗡 𝗙𝗥𝗘𝗘?
✅ 𝗘𝗡𝗥𝗢𝗟𝗟 𝗜𝗡 𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝟭-𝗢𝗡-𝟭 𝗢𝗡𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗘 𝗥𝗘𝗛𝗔𝗕 𝗖𝗢𝗔𝗖𝗛𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗡𝗢𝗪! ✅
⬆️ 𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗞 𝗜𝗡 𝗧𝗛𝗘 𝗕𝗜𝗢! ⬆️

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Do you complain about chronically stiff and tight hamstrings?

A combination of stretching, releasing and strengthening can all help permanently relieve excessive tension in the hamstrings. Being a biarticular muscle and crossing both the hip and knee joint, it is important to address this muscle from where it originates and inserts.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗛𝗔𝗠𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Stand and place one foot on a bench or chair with the toes pointed towards the ceiling. Place both hands on your thigh and slowly lean forward by hinging your hips backwards until a stretch is felt in your hamstrings.

2️⃣ 𝗛𝗔𝗠𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗞𝗕 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Place a kettlebell on the ground with the handles perpendicular to the body. Half kneel on the ground and place the upper portion of the hamstrings on top of the handle of the kettlebell. Slowly sink your weight onto the kettlebell and drive the knee forward.

3️⃣ 𝗛𝗔𝗠𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗥𝗢𝗖𝗞𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞𝗦:
Half kneel on the ground with both legs bent to roughly 90 degrees with the hands on the floor. Rock your weight back onto the rear leg while straightening out the front leg and raising the toes up to the ceiling. Reverse the movement to the starting position.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐓𝐄𝐗𝐓 𝐍𝐄𝐂𝐊! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Text neck (also commonly known as anterior head carriage) is a term used to describe when the head excessively travels forward from the neck.

Some possible factors that can contribute to text neck are prolonged periods of poor posture (texting, in front of the computer, etc) along with muscular imbalances created from repetitive motion and possibly overuse. Strengthening the muscles that are responsible for keeping the head over the shoulders is key to restoring balance in the area.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗘𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗬 𝗥𝗔𝗜𝗦𝗘𝗦:
Sit on a ground with a foam roller in between the wall and shoulder blades. Sit as tall as possible with the head over the shoulders. Perform a standard chin tuck while lifting the arms overhead and lowering them back down.

2️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗖𝗛𝗜𝗡 𝗧𝗨𝗖𝗞𝗦:
Lay face down on a bench with a mini band around the wrist and back of the head. Pull the wrist apart and have the forearms parallel to the ground. Push the back of your head into the band and hold this position for 30 seconds.

3️⃣ 𝗚𝗟𝗨𝗧𝗘 𝗕𝗥𝗜𝗗𝗚𝗘 𝗖𝗛𝗜𝗡 𝗧𝗨𝗖𝗞:
Sit on the ground and rest the back of your head on a bench. Perform a standard glute bridge and lift the hips off the ground while actively pushing the back of your head into the bench. Focus on keeping your torso parallel to the ground.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐅𝐈𝐗 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐂𝐈𝐀𝐓𝐈𝐂𝐀! [piriformis syndrome] 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The piriformis is a muscle located in your buttock area. It is responsible for moving the hip along with providing stability in the area. However, if it becomes too tight, it can cause a variety of dysfunctions such as sciatica and low back pain.

The sciatica nerve passes through the piriformis muscle and can become impinged from a number of factors such as long periods of sitting, muscular imbalances and repetitive motion. A combination of stretching, releasing and strengthening can all help restore balance in the area.

1️⃣ 𝗣𝗜𝗥𝗜𝗙𝗢𝗥𝗠𝗜𝗦 𝗥𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗔𝗦𝗘:
Place the musculature of the outside of the hip on top of a foam roller. Cross the leg over the opposite thigh. Place your hands on the ground for support while slowly rolling the tissue over the foam roller.

2️⃣ 𝗣𝗜𝗥𝗜𝗙𝗢𝗥𝗠𝗜𝗦 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Sit on a chair and cross one leg over the other and allow the knee to drop down towards the ground. Slowly hinge forward from the hips without rounding from the spine until a stretch is felt in the gluteal muscles.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗙𝗜𝗥𝗘 𝗛𝗬𝗗𝗥𝗔𝗡𝗧𝗦:
Place a hip band around the knee and stand facing away from the wall. Place one foot on the wall with the hands on the hips. Push one knee out and away from the body while preventing the opposite knee from caving inwards.
.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐋𝐎𝐖𝐄𝐑 𝐁𝐀𝐂𝐊! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Lower back pain/tension is one of the most common complaints in both the general population and in athletes.

Stretching and/or mobilization of the area can help loosen the soft tissue in the area along with providing healthy movement in the joints. Incorporating these stretches and releases into your stretching routine can help do that. It is also important to follow up with strengthening exercises to help cement the results.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗨𝗣𝗜𝗡𝗘 𝗛𝗜𝗣 𝗧𝗪𝗜𝗦𝗧:
Lay face up with both legs extended and arms directly to the side. Lift one leg up towards the ceiling and then to the side. Lower the leg back down to the starting position and repeat on the opposite side. Be sure to have the arm in contact with the ground at all times.

2️⃣ 𝗣𝗥𝗢𝗡𝗘 𝗦𝗖𝗢𝗥𝗣𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Lay face down with the arms directly extended to the sides. Bend one leg to roughly 90 degrees and cross it over to the opposite side while simultaneously looking away. Drop the leg back to the starting position and repeat on the opposite side.

3️⃣ 𝗟𝗢𝗪𝗘𝗥 𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞 𝗦𝗘𝗟𝗙 𝗥𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗔𝗦𝗘:
Lay face up with a lacrosse ball on the side of the lower back (in between the lower rib and the pelvis). Pull the same side knee towards your chest with your hands (do not use your hip!) and slowly drop towards the same side until a release is felt.

▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Runner's knee is a general term that is used to describe pain located in front of the knee.

There are many possible factors that can contribute to runner's knee such as poor running mechanics, muscular imbalances and simply repetitive strain/overuse. While foam rolling and stretching the area can help provide temporary relief, it is important to also strengthen the tissues that cross over the knee joint itself.

1️⃣ 𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗩𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗛𝗘𝗘𝗟 𝗧𝗔𝗣𝗦:
Stand on an elevated platform with a dumbbell held in front of the chest. Lower one heel towards the ground while simultaneously pushing the dumbbell forward as a counter balance. Stand back up by driving the entire foot into the platform.

2️⃣ 𝗛𝗘𝗘𝗟 𝗧𝗔𝗣 𝗛𝗢𝗟𝗗𝗦:
Start in the same position as the Elevated Heel Taps and holding onto a stationary object such as a squat rack or door frame. Lower one leg behind you and towards the ground. Relaxing your grip around the squat rack will increase the difficulty of the exercise.

3️⃣ 𝗪𝗔𝗟𝗟 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗟𝗜𝗙𝗧 𝗢𝗙𝗙𝗦:
Start by resting the back of your head, shoulder blades and hips against a wall with the legs bent to roughly 90 degrees. Straighten one leg out directly in front of you while keeping your hips leveled. Lower the leg back down and repeat on the opposite side.

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
A lack of mobility can cause other joints in the body to compensate and manifest into dysfunctions and possibly even injuries.

When it comes to mobility, it is important to mobilize joints that are designed to be mobile such as the ankles, hips and thoracic spine. Mobilizing these joints will give you the best bang for your buck. Stabilizing the joints in between these joints (such as the knees, lower back and upper back) should also be prioritized when it comes to cementing your results.

1️⃣ 𝗧𝗛𝗢𝗥𝗔𝗖𝗜𝗖 𝗘𝗫𝗧𝗘𝗡𝗦𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦 𝗢𝗡 𝗥𝗢𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗥:
Lay face up on the ground and rest the mid back on top of a foam roller. Interlock your fingers together and behind your neck and keep the core engaged. Slowly wrap the spine over and around the foam roller and repeat.

2️⃣ 𝗙𝗥𝗢𝗡𝗧 𝗙𝗢𝗢𝗧 𝗦𝗣𝗟𝗜𝗧 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧:
Place one foot on an elevated surface such as a plyometric box or bench with the opposite leg behind you. Lunge forward until the knee passes over the toes while keeping the heel planted on the ground at all times. Push off back into the starting position and repeat.

3️⃣ 𝗛𝗔𝗣𝗣𝗬 𝗕𝗔𝗕𝗬 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Lay face up on the ground and pull the legs in towards your chest. Grab a hold of the big toes with your hands. Pull the feet over and away from the body until a stretch is felt in the hips. Be sure to keep the lower back on the ground at all times.
.
